NEW DELHI: Internationally acclaimed sand artist Sudarsan Pattnaik now has another world record to his name. On the eve of World AIDS Day, Pattnaik created the world's longest red ribbon on the Odisha's famed Puri beach to generate awareness about the fatal disease.

The red ribbon is the universal symbol of awareness and support for people living with HIV-AIDS. Pattnaik's attempt to recreate the ribbon on sand is 800 feet long and 400 feet wide, an immense sand art which could only be captured with a drone camera.


Read this story in Malayalam

The Limca Book of Records took cognizance of Pattnaik's feat and his name has been registered in the world record for the longest sand art ribbon.


An aerial view of my SandArt for Limca book of World record by creating 800ft long and 400 ft wide sand Red Ribbon… https://t.co/rTUldinp1Q— Sudarsan Pattnaik (@sudarsansand) 1512056696000

Pattnaik, known for his immaculate art work with sand, shares messages related to almost every topic across India ranging from social, political, environmental concerns and sports at Puri beach. 

Earlier this year, he created the world's tallest sand castle on Puri beach which earned him a place in the Guinness World Records.


